fr:tree.fr:mainmatter:
For this note, we will consider a maximization linear program. Namely, an optimization problem of the following form
\begin {align*} \max _{\mathbf {x}} \quad &\mathbf {c}^{\top } \mathbf {x} \\ \text {s.t.} \quad &A\mathbf {x} \leq b .\end {align*}
In the spirit of lagrange multipliers, we can also get a dual formulation. To do so, we add a multiplier y_i for each constraint i.e. y_i \mathbf {a}_i^T \mathbf {x} \leq y_i b_i we then consider the summed constraint (which ends up being tight enough), \mathbf {y}^T A \mathbf {x} \leq \mathbf {y}^T\mathbf {b} To relate this back to our primal problem, we enforce the additional constraint that \mathbf {y}^T A = \mathbf {c}^T \iff A \mathbf {y} = \mathbf {c} . The reason for this is that for a feasible \mathbf {y}, we have \mathbf {y}^T A \mathbf {x} = \mathbf {c}^T \mathbf {x} \leq \mathbf {y}^T \mathbf {b}, so that \mathbf {y}^T \mathbf {b} is an upper bound for our primal objective \mathbf {c}^T \mathbf {x} . Intuitively, to recover \mathbf {c}^T \mathbf {x}^* , we can just minimize over \mathbf {y}, resulting in the following dual program
\begin {align*} \min _{\mathbf {y}} \quad &\mathbf {b}^T\mathbf {y} \\ \text {s.t.} \quad &A \mathbf {y} = \mathbf {c} \\ & \mathbf {y} \geq 0 .\end {align*}

    Let \rho (s) \in  \mathbb {R}^{|\mathcal {S}|}  be the initial state distribution. Then consider the following LP 
    \begin {align*}
\begin {array}{ll} \displaystyle  \max _{V \in  \mathbb {R}^{|\mathcal {S}|}} & \displaystyle  \sum _{s \in  \mathcal {S}} \rho (s) V(s) \\ \text {s.t.} & V(s) \leq  r(s,a) + \gamma  \sum _{s'} P(s' \mid  s,a) \, V(s'), \qquad  \forall  s,a. \end {array}
    \end {align*}
    Translating this into our standard form, we have

\mathbf {c} \in  \mathbb {R}^{|\mathcal {S}|} with c_s = \rho (s)

A \in  \mathbb {R}^{|\mathcal {S}| \times  |\mathcal {A}| \times  |\mathcal {S}|} with A_{(s,a),s'} = -\delta _{s,s'} + \gamma  P(s'|s,a).

    Substituting this in for the dual formulation gives us
    \begin {align*}
& \min _{y(s,a) \geq  0} & & \sum _{s,a} r(s,a) \, y(s,a) \\ & \text {s.t.} & & \sum _{a} y(s,a) - \gamma  \sum _{s',a'} P(s \mid  s',a') \, y(s',a') = \rho (s), \qquad  \forall  s
    \end {align*}
    Here \mathbf {y} can be seen as the discounted occupancy measure. This allows us to recover a randomized optimal policy via
    \mathbb {P}(\pi ^*(s) = a) = \frac {y(s, a)}{\sum _{a} y(s,a)}

